..I thought in order to have a good drift, the indicator needs to be upstream of the fly???? <br>
Dano <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flyfishar>FlyFishAR</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 507<br> <font color=#000000>(8/27/03 9:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=146.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.flyfishingarkansas.com/Photo%20Gallery/tn_j.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Dead Drift</span><hr size=1> Dan:<br>
<br>
Lots of people fish the way that you are describing. It &quot;is&quot; the best way to get a natural drift. However, it &quot;is not&quot; the most effective way to catch fish. If the indicator is upstream from the fly it has to &quot;pass&quot; the fly in order for it to get tension and then indicate a strike. If you are fishing with a 6 foot section between your fly and indicator your indicator might have to drift as much as 8 feet before you could indicate a strike. The guys in Alaska teach keeping the fly down stream from the indicator to keep a proper drift. This is completely wrong. <br>
<br>
The real secret is to balance the amount of weight. If you have the correct amount of weight your indicator will drag slightly as the shot bounces along the bottom. However, the fly will be drifting naturally since the current on the bottom is slower than the current on the top. I've included a quick drawing to illustrate what I'm talking about. Notice fish #1 will have an indication of a take almost immediately. But fish #2 will have to have the indicator travel some distance before the strike is shown.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.msnusers.com/mypicture?user=4263~5AAAAAAABE7AELpVKLbYUEw2cpu8D6N6X8eAkitL50XCHBwSjvQ!vHjw$$~5AAAAAAACGOAdkNFlfyZ5I3bEaMQ*wi5FsWbimcqbj3yA$" target="top">For Indicator Dead Drift Picture &quot;Click Here&quot;</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
 <br>
I guided a man a a while back that fished exactly that method. When we first started out he was having some difficulty catching fish. We worked on changing the style of drift and he caught maybe 35 fish that afternoon. I could &quot;see&quot; the fish taking the fly but he couldn't see his indicator move so he wouldn't set the hook. Once the indicator was placed down stream of the fly he started seeing the takes.<br>
<br>
John<br>
